<subSubSection id="99C442339D21ADDD91C8F65914606671" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A1824A9B912D187331AE404907EC8167" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName id="13EC7B4647D90369A44770786119FF10" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="attenboroughianum">Hieracium attenboroughianum</taxonomicName>
is a member of 
<taxonomicName id="83B15534B7451D1B3888D27C3EC84488" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Stelligera">Hieracium section Stelligera Zahn</taxonomicName>
, with a welldeveloped basal rosette and few or no stem leaves, with rigid simple hairs and medium to large capitula. Within Section Stelligera, it is a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="7138E45F5F863E8F651B11C20A16C9FF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="britannicum">H. britannicum</taxonomicName>
group (Sell &amp; West, 1968; Sell &amp; Murrell, 2006), which are a group of closely related species of calcareous substrates which may have diverged through geographic isolation and minor mutation from a more widespread parent species. It can be separated from these seven related species as below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B3EAC0F7B6E0E5C07821509777FB3EF" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName id="27C39EFDB23C4FF3DCCF6B4EC785B5F2" authority="F. Hanb" authorityName="F. Hanb" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="britannicum">Hieracium britannicum F. Hanb</taxonomicName>
., which is endemic to Derbyshire and Staffordshire, differs in having dense stellate hairs and numerous simple hairs on the involucral bracts (sparse stellate hairs and sparse simple hairs on the involucral bracts in 
<taxonomicName id="A5C9B254A98C7A0E4048B8569000F836" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="attenboroughianum">H. attenboroughianum</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F815C95916BCD3DAE731BCEEA326B676" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName id="ADBD5F47328D4B55028BDF143B778840" authority="Pugsley" authorityName="Pugsley" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="britanniciforme">
Hieracium britanniciforme 
<authority id="FD896AB2647E60239612DB912FFF9B00">Pugsley</authority>
</taxonomicName>
differs in having larger capitula 40-50 mm across and large dark spots on the leaves which have many long simple hairs on the upper surface (smaller capitula and unspotted leaves with few or no simple hairs on the upper surface in 
<taxonomicName id="E6E015720909304866B5B1DE72ACE212" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="attenboroughianum">H. attenboroughianum</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B37CD3F8C3C5C4C0E453833F3FE5BF8A" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" type="mainText">
<taxonomicName id="5B0FB4808F4D88A84694946A92734D0B" authority="P.D. Sell" authorityName="P.D. Sell" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="britannicoides">
Hieracium britannicoides 
<authority id="2A47856BC0F7964E01F25E4BD4C96BC1">P.D. Sell</authority>
</taxonomicName>
, which is endemic to North Wales, differs in having flat mid-green or slightly glaucous leaves with many, long simple eglandular hairs on the petioles, and numerous medium simple eglandular hairs and few glandular hairs on the involucral bracts (cupped, dark green leaves and sparse medium simple eglandular hairs and many glandular hairs on the involucral bracts in 
<taxonomicName id="6D3C8D9DA5F17AE445DDED4D4CF9C283" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="attenboroughianum">H. attenboroughianum</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="691AC64B236E095CF359549B806762A2" pageId="2" pageNumber="174">
<paragraph id="5CCF4610DC457408172D7365BA314EFC" pageId="2" pageNumber="174" type="caption">
